233. Number Of Digit One

Average Rating: 3.77 (30 votes)

June 23, 2017  |  20.8K views

Given an integer n, count the total number of digit 1 appearing in all non-negative integers less than or equal to n.

Example:

Input: 13
Output: 6 
Explanation: Digit 1 occurred in the following numbers: 1, 10, 11, 12, 13.
  • Solution
    • Approach #1 Brute force [Time Limit Exceeded]
    • Approach #2 Solve it mathematically [Accepted]

Solution

Approach #1 Brute force [Time Limit Exceeded]

Intuition

Do as directed in question.

Algorithm

  • Iterate over iii from 111 to nnn:
  • Convert iii to string and count ’1’\text{'1'}’1’ in each integer string
  • Add count of ’1’\text{'1'}’1’ in each string to the sum, say countrcountrcountr

Complexity Analysis

  • Time complexity: O(n∗log10(n))O(n*log_{10}(n))O(n∗log10​(n)).
  • We iterate from 111 to nnn

  • In each iteration, we convert integer to string and count '1' in string which takes linear time in number of digits in iii, which is log10(n)log_{10}(n)log10​(n).

  • Space complexity: O(log10(n))O(log_{10}(n))O(log10​(n)) Extra space for the countr and the converted string str\text{str}str.

Approach #2 Solve it mathematically [Accepted]

Intuition

In Approach #1, we manually calculated the number of all the ′1′'1'′1′s in the digits, but this is very slow. Hence, we need a way to find a pattern in the way ′1′'1'′1′s (or for that matter any digit) appears in the numbers. We could then use the pattern to formulate the answer.

Consider the 111s in ones\text{ones}ones place , tens\text{tens}tens place, hundreds\text{hundreds}hundreds place and so on... An analysis has been performed in the following figure.

From the figure, we can see that from digit '1' at ones\text{ones}ones place repeat in group of 1 after interval of 101010. Similarly, '1' at tens\text{tens}tens place repeat in group of 10 after interval of 100100100. This can be formulated as (n/(i∗10))∗i(n/(i*10))*i(n/(i∗10))∗i.

Also, notice that if the digit at tens\text{tens}tens place is ’1’\text{'1'}’1’, then the number of terms with ’1’s\text{'1's}’1’s is increased by x+1x+1x+1, if the number is say "ab1x"\text{"ab1x"}"ab1x". As if digits at tens\text{tens}tens place is greater than 111, then all the 101010 occurances of numbers with ′1′'1'′1′ at tens\text{tens}tens place have taken place, hence, we add 101010. This is formluated as min⁡(max⁡((n mod (i*10))−i+1,0),i){\min(\max((\text{n mod (i*10)} )-i+1,0),i)}min(max((n mod (i*10))−i+1,0),i).

Lets take an example, say n=1234n= 1234n=1234.

No of ’1’\text{'1'}’1’ in ones\text{ones}ones place = 1234/101234/101234/10(corresponding to 1,11,21,...1221) + min⁡(4,1)\min(4,1)min(4,1)(corresponding to 1231) =124124124

No of ’1’\text{'1'}’1’ in tens\text{tens}tens place = (1234/100)∗10(1234/100)*10(1234/100)∗10(corresponding to 10,11,12,...,110,111,...1919) +min⁡(21,10)\min(21,10)min(21,10)(corresponding to 1210,1211,...1219)=130130130

No of ’1’\text{'1'}’1’ in hundreds\text{hundreds}hundreds place = (1234/1000)∗100(1234/1000)*100(1234/1000)∗100(corresponding to 100,101,12,...,199) +min⁡(135,100)\min(135,100)min(135,100)(corresponding to 1100,1101...1199)=200200200

No of ’1’\text{'1'}’1’ in thousands\text{thousands}thousands place = (1234/10000)∗10000(1234/10000)*10000(1234/10000)∗10000 +min⁡(235,1000)\min(235,1000)min(235,1000)(corresponding to 1000,1001,...1234)=235235235

Therefore, Total = 124+130+200+235=689124+130+200+235 = 689124+130+200+235=689.

Herein, one formula has been devised, but many other formulae can be devised for faster implementations, but the essence and complexity remains the same. The users are encouraged to try to divise their own version of solution using the mathematical concepts.

Algorithm

  • Iterate over iii from 111 to nnn incrementing by 101010 each time:
  • Add (n/(i∗10))∗i(n/(i*10))*i(n/(i∗10))∗i to countr\text{countr}countr representing the repetition of groups of $$i$ sizes after each (i∗10)(i*10)(i∗10) interval.
  • Add min⁡(max⁡((n mod (i*10))−i+1,0),i){\min(\max((\text{n mod (i*10)} )-i+1,0),i)}min(max((n mod (i*10))−i+1,0),i) to countr\text{countr}countr representing the additional digits dependant on the digit in iiith place as described in intuition.

Complexity analysis

  • Time complexity: O(log10(n))O(log_{10}(n))O(log10​(n)).

  • No of iterations equal to the number of digits in n which is log10(n)log_{10}(n)log10​(n)

  • Space complexity: O(1)O(1)O(1) space required.

java:

class Solution {
    public int countDigitOne(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return 0;
        }
        int m = n;
        int sum = 0;
        int e = 1;
        while (n > 0) {
            int r = n % 10;
            n /= 10;
            if (r == 0) {
                sum += n * e;
            } else if (r > 1) {
                sum += (n + 1) * e;
            } else { // r == 1
                sum += m - n * 9 * e - e + 1;
            }
            e *= 10;
        }
        return sum;
    }
}

Here is my C# solution (and my first comment (: )

public int CountDigitOne(int n)
{
int count = 0;
string temp = string.Empty;

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++)
        {
            if (i.ToString().Contains("1"))
            {
                temp = i.ToString();

                count += temp.Where(item => item == '1').Count();
            }
        }

        return count;
    }

JAVA Solution:

I am not sure why it is giving me time exceeded for this solution. Could some one please explain me why
and also if you have a better solution or any changes in this solution. Thanks in advance.

class Solution {
public int countDigitOne(int n) {
if (n<=0){return 0;}
Map<Integer, Integer> frequencyMap = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();
int low = 1;
while (low<=n) {
int temp = low;
while (temp > 0) {
int last_digit = temp % 10;
frequencyMap.put(last_digit, frequencyMap.getOrDefault(last_digit, 0) + 1);
temp = temp / 10;
}
low++;
}
return frequencyMap.get(1);
}
}
